		<template id="meeting">
	        <div>
	            <h1><b>Weekly meetings</b></h1>
	            <p class="text-muted">
	                Once you’ve deployed your CRM, it’s time to grow your revenues. 
	                Start by setting up a continuous improvement approach.
	                We recommend you to organize weekly sales meeting with the team 
	                during which you will do a pipeline review.
	            </p>
	            <p>
	                <strong>Organize weekly sales meetings</strong><br/>
	                Start the pipeline review by the big picture; 
	                revenues and number of opportunities by stage, 
	                by expected closing date and by salespeople. 
	                The analysis of the pipeline by stage will answer 
	                questions like "do we have enough leads?" and "how 
	                should we use our time between qualified and new prospects?".
	             </p>
	             <p>
	                The analysis of the pipeline by expected closing date will 
	                help your team efficiently forecast its future revenues. 
	                Finally, the analysis of the pipeline by salespeople will 
	                allow you to identify mistakes or best practices amongst the 
	                team to replicate to all salespeople.
	            </p>
	            <p>
	                <strong>Analyze the best opportunities together</strong><br/>
	                Once the big picture is clear, have a look at the best opportunities. 
	                Start from stages on the right (negotiation, proposal, ...) and review 
	                the biggest opportunities one by one with the team. For every deal, 
	                identify risks and opportunities; check the next action and expected 
	                closing, check latest customer feedback, review the quotation, etc.
	            </p>
	            <p>
	                By asking a few questions, you should quickly understand what's good 
	                and bad in your team's sales practices; What are the pain points? 
	                Who decides? What's the next action?...
	            </p>
	            <p>
	                <strong>Forecast the future revenues</strong><br/>
	                One can check the maturity of a sales team by its ability to 
	                forecasts future revenues for the next months or quarter. 
	                To train the team to forecast efficiently, during the first 
	                sales meeting of the month/quarter, you should fix expected 
	                revenues of the next two months/quarters. This will allow the 
	                team to compare expected revenues and real numbers afterwards.
	            </p>
	            <p>
	                Depending on the complexity of the business, it may take 
	                between 6 months and 18 months for a new sales team to 
	                efficiently forecasts future revenues.
	            </p>
	        </div>
		</template>

		<template id="boost_sale">
	        <div class="text-left">
	            <h1><b>Boosting Sales</b></h1>
	            <p class="text-muted">
	                A systematic organization and a clear process is what will turn your 
	                best salespersons into excellent ones. Great sales process are aligned 
	                with the customer mind and buying cycle.  As an example, if you follow 
	                a "Sollution Selling" sales cycle (Territory, Qualified, Qualified Sponsors, 
	                Proposition ...), an opportunity should be set as "Qualified Sponsors" 
	                when THE BYUER admited his pains, not when YOU understood his needs. 
	                As an other example, an opportunity should be set as "Negociation" 
	                when the buyer came back to you to discuss the price, not when you did a 
	                follow up call.
	            </p>
	            <p>
	                <strong>Check on your team discipline</strong><br/>
	                During the firsts months of the implementation of the opportunities 
	                pipeline, you will have to ensure that your team follows the defined 
	                requirements at every stage. It's critical to continuously train your 
	                team on the requirements to move opportunities from one stage to another one. 
	                By reviewing the best opportunities one by one during the weekly sales meeting, 
	                you will have to continuously check that your sales process is aligned with 
	                the customer one.
	            </p>
	            <p>
	                <strong>Remove the blocking points</strong><br/>
	                You will achieve great improvement with an efficient follow up 
	                of the pipeline. But to achieve excellence in your sales 
	                organization, you need to provide sales tools to the team. 
	                For every stage of the opportunities pipeline, identify the blocking points 
	                and create documents to train the team.
	            </p>
	            <p>Here are a few examples:</p>
	            <section>
                    <div class="row">
                        <div class="well well-lg col-md-4 mb32">
                            <strong>New:</strong><br/>
                            <li>Phone scripts (use the google doc spreadsheet to attach templates automatically to every opportunity)</li>
                            <li>Qualification form (you can use the survey app for this)</li>
                            <li> Templates of Emails</li>
                            <br/>
                            <strong>Qualified:</strong>
                            <li>List of Possible Pain Points by segment/profile</li>
                            <li>VIP letter to potential sponsors</li>
                        </div>
                        <div class="well well-lg col-md-4 mb32" style="margin-left:50px">
                            <strong>Propositions:</strong><br/>
                            <li>Templates of quotations</li>
                            <li>Competition Matrix comparing prices</li>
                            <br/>
                            <strong>Negotiation:</strong><br/>
                            <li>Motivation letter from the management</li>
                        </div>
                    </div>
                    <div class="row">
                        <p>
                            You don't need to review Lost opportunities at every sales meeting 
                            but it's a good practice to do it once a month. Ask your team to set 
                            tags on opportunities to identify Lost reasons and do statistics on them. 
                            Example of tags to create: no budget, competition, no pain found, etc.
                        </p>
                    </div>
	            </section>
	        </div>
		</template>

